TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

###########################
#  Setup

Context("Numeric");
Context()->variables->add(y=>"Real");

# integrating about x-axis
$a = random(2, 4, 1); #upper bound
$f1 = Formula("3*x^3 - 2")->reduce;  
$f_int = Formula("pi*(9/7*x^7 - 3*x^4 - 1/3*x^3 + 4*x)"); #integrated for volume around x-axis
$f2_up = $f_int ->eval(x=>$a); #f_int eval at upper bound
$f2_low = $f_int ->eval(x=>Real(1)); #f_int eval at lower bound


#now add it all together
$ans = $f2_up - $f2_low; #now adding upper and lower

###########################
#  Main text

BEGIN_PGML

Consider the region generated by the curves [`y=[$f1]`], [`y=x`], and [`x=[$a]`]. Determine which method you think would be easiest to use to calculate the volume generated when the region is rotated around the [`x`]-axis.  Then use your chosen method to find the volume.

Volume: [_______________]{$ans} units cubed [@ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") @]*


END_PGML

